    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="background">
Many thanks to Sharon Traweek for succintly expressing the particular 
contribution that ethnographic work can make in reframing certain notions 
of science criticism.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="6" relname="span">  Given long-term, on-site commitments to explore 
the situated knowledge of lab or clinic, the scientists, technicians, 
clinicians, et al. with whom we work are interlocutors, not 
epistemological quarry;</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="7" relname="span"> often enough, as David Hakken suggests, they are 
sources, not merely objects of critique, of our work as well as their 
own. </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="8" relname="span"> We find ourselves joined through epistemic alignments [Rouse] or 
partial connections [Haraway] that link local and translocal knowledges; </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="evaluation">
surely this is more productive terrain for projects of global citizenship 
at the end of the century than the pugilistic rhetoric of the &apos;culture 
wars.&apos;</segment>
